@pjain1 thanks for taking a look at this

on line 468 of KafkaIndexTask, the nextOffsets map is updated based on the currentOffset taken from the message itself so this should be accurate regardless if messages were skipped or not (the +1 being to read the next message, which might wind up not existing and it would skip ahead again)
```
nextOffsets.put(record.partition(), record.offset() + 1);
```

As for the equality check vs a greater than or equal, I was considering this and decided against it because with the current implementation, even with skipping offsets, getting an offset value greater than the endOffset would be considered a bug in the logic. The ending offset is set by the supervisor after the taskDuration elapses and is based on the latest offset any of the replicas made it to before they were paused, which means that this has to be a valid offset, so if one replica read a certain offset value and another one skipped that offset, that shouldn't be treated as correct behavior

@pjain1 I updated the proposal with some more details on the Basic HTTP auth implementation.

@nishantmonu51 I added a section to Future Work regarding row/column-level authorization. I'm leaning towards supporting that through a "View" system.

Regarding extensibility of the RBAC model, after thinking more on this, my current stance is that someone wishing to plug in their own RBAC system should implement their own AuthorizationManager vs. providing additional extension points within the built-in AuthorizationManager.

The data model used by other systems would generally be more sophisticated than the basic RBAC model proposed here (for example, the Athenz system linked by @pjain1 has more concepts like domain namespaces and services). 

I don't think we could capture every data model variation if the extension point is at the User/Role/Permission level, and it would be cleaner/more useful to not impose such assumptions on an extension implementer.

@himanshug I revised the proposal to mention that the built-in implementations will be contained inside a core extension.

@nishantmonu51 @himanshug re: useBuiltInTables() is eliminated from the proposed interfaces, the coordinator APIs will now be disabled unless the core extension's implementations are in use.

@himanshug I thought you mentioned a QTL related reason too on the dev sync.

I think it's clear that for combining overlords and coordinators, we need to be able to support updating MMs first and then overlords (so overlord/coordinator can be done simultaneously). And that's a useful feature for simplifying deployments, so imo it'd be good to fully support it. So I think at least we should formalize that we support that.

If we need to keep supporting the other order (overlord first, then MM) then, imo, we should consider formalizing that we support both orders.
